             sworn. Examined by Mr.<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="180604160014"></xptr>Knapp. I live in Horshoe-alley, the prisoner has lodged in my house ever since a week after Christmass.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18060416-8-person120">
                  JOHN 
                  ARMSTRONG
               <interp inst="t18060416-8-person120" type="surname" value="ARMSTRONG"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18060416-8-person120" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18060416-8-person120" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn. Examined by Mr. Knapp. Q. You are one of the police officers of Worship-street. - A. Yes, I apprehended the prisoner on Tuesday the 8th of April, about a quarter before ten at night; I went in company with Mr. Miller, Vickery, and Kennedy, into Broad-arrow court, Grub-street, up one pair of stairs, at one Sadler's, a baker, there I apprehended the prisoner, I told him I apprehended him for some bags found in his room: he said he knew nothing about them.</p>
               <p>(The bags produced and indentified by Shanklie.)</p>
               <p>The prisoner called three witnesses, who gave him a good character.</p>
               <p>
